```

Setting `innerHTML = ''` detaches DOM nodes but listeners and closures referencing them remain in memory until garbage-collected. Using a `DocumentFragment` batches DOM reflows, capturing `name` per iteration avoids closure pitfalls, and the `while` loop via `removeChild` ensures proper detachment so listeners can be released.

local_answer:
The issue you're encountering is indeed related to memory leaks. In your code, the `renderItems` function repeatedly appends new `div` elements to the `container` element, and the `clearItems` function clears the `innerHTML` of the `container` element. However, the problem lies in the fact that you are not removing the event listeners from the dynamically created elements when you clear the container.

When you clear the `innerHTML` of the `container`, the event listeners attached to the dynamically created elements are not removed, leading to memory leaks. The event listeners remain attached to the DOM nodes, causing them to accumulate over time and eventually lead to performance issues.

To fix this, you need to ensure that the event listeners are properly removed when you clear the container. Here's how you can modify your code:

```javascript
function renderItems(items) {
    const container = document.getElementById('container');
    for (let i = 0; i < items.length; i++) {
        const el = document.createElement('div');
        el.textContent = items[i].name;
        el.addEventListener('click', () => alert(items[i].name));
        container.appendChild(el);
    }
}

function clearItems() {
    const container = document.getElementById('container');
    while (container.firstChild) {
        container.removeChild(container.firstChild);
    }
    // Remove event listeners from all elements in the container
    const elements = container.querySelectorAll('div');
    elements.forEach(element => element.removeEventListener('click', () => alert(items[i].name)));
}
```

In this updated version:
1. The `clearItems` function now uses `while (container.firstChild)` to remove all child nodes from the `container` until it is empty.
2. It then uses `container.querySelectorAll('div')` to select all `div` elements within the `container`.
3. Finally, it iterates over these elements and removes the event listener from each one.

This ensures that all event listeners are properly removed when the container is cleared, preventing memory leaks and improving the performance of your page.

